FYI any CO2 production from a cow is carbon neutral. The carbon gets fixed by the plant and then respirated by the cow.

But please note I'm not saying that milk is worse than almond-based products. Actually, I think if someone is making the decision for environmental-based reasons alone, there are LOTS of reasons by dairy makes much more sense than almond-based products - like water requirements.

CO2 production from dairy comes from the cows, not the transport... cows produce methane, while almond trees do not. But with regards to transport... we move milk a lot less far than almonds. Almond-based products from California to Quebec travel 5000+ km by truck.

We actually did the math on this (because we are #environment and #sustainability nerds) and the numbers were staggering. Milk is worse CO2-wise, but almonds use a ridiculous amount of water to grow and process. Happy to share the report if you'd like!
